# Fluff Date: 2026-03-13 13:07:08
<overview>
<p>The Life Boat is a five-ton Small Craft built for a single purpose: keeping six people alive long enough to be rescued. Introduced in 2478, it became a fixture aboard JumpShips and DropShips across the Inner Sphere, carried by military and civilian vessels alike. Deliberately simple and inexpensive, it was never intended to fight, maneuver, or operate independently. The design carries enough life support and emergency provisions to sustain its passengers until a recovery vessel can reach them, with a passive power system that keeps the distress beacon broadcasting indefinitely. Its longevity as an essentially unchanged design reflects how little room there is to improve on a craft defined entirely by its constraints.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Life Boat carries no weapons and cannot re-enter a planetary atmosphere, restricting it to space operations only. Propulsion consists of attitude correction jets that provide basic orientation control but no meaningful thrust. Once deployed, the craft drifts and waits for recovery. Passengers have no ability to maneuver toward help or avoid hazards, and survival depends entirely on the distress beacon being detected and a recovery craft being dispatched.</p><p>Life support sustains up to six passengers for 24 to 30 days. Food supplies last approximately 16 days. Power comes from a solar energy collector sail drawn from JumpShip charging sail technology, which continuously recharges the batteries without consuming fuel. This powers lighting, life support, and the distress beacon indefinitely. The beacon's photochemical sail coating also reflects electromagnetic frequencies used by deep-space tracking systems, making the craft highly visible to search operations even without active communication. These two features, passive power and continuous beacon broadcast, define the Life Boat's operational value.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Life Boat is standard emergency equipment aboard JumpShips and DropShips throughout the Inner Sphere, carried in launch racks, cargo bays, and docking hardpoints across military and civilian fleets. No faction considers it a combat asset, but its presence reflects its status as essential infrastructure rather than optional equipment. Life Boats are commonly recovered at debris fields following large engagements, found drifting with sails extended and beacons broadcasting, their occupants awaiting retrieval.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Life Boat entered service in 2478, developed in response to the growing hazards of deep-space travel as interstellar commerce expanded beyond the early colonization waves. Early spacecraft accidents, particularly JumpShip failures in uninhabited systems, exposed the inadequacy of basic life support equipment when rescue could take weeks to arrive. The solar sail power system addressed the central failure of earlier emergency designs, battery depletion, by providing passive, indefinite power to both life support and the distress beacon without any fuel requirement.</p><p>The Star League codified Life Boats as mandatory survival equipment aboard registered spacecraft, and production spread across dozens of worlds with no centralized manufacturer. The design's simplicity kept it viable through the Succession Wars, when more sophisticated emergency systems were lost along with the technology to maintain them. It has remained in continuous production ever since, changed only in minor details, across nearly seven centuries of uninterrupted service.</p>
</history>

